{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280602012/1937092001/0800.xml":{"full_text":"August Kilowatt Report\nShows 10 Per Cent Rise\nin District Sales.\nBY EDWARD C. STONE.\nContinued business expansion in the\nCapital in August is indicated by the\nPotomac Electric Power Co.\u2019s latest\nmonthly report showing that kilowatt\nhour sales totaled 59,129,588 in com\nparison with 53,718.863 in August,\n1936, an increase of 5.410,725, or 10.07\nper cent.\nThis advance followed a stepping up\nIn electricity output during each month\nso far this year as compared with the\nlike period in 1936, the monthly com\nparisons revealing the upward trend\nbeing as follows:\nMonth. 1937. 1936.\nJanuary _ 55,008.550 52,964.846\nFebruary 52,776,655 49.674,319\nMarch 52,704,429 49,961,534\nApril.. 51,393,092 49,186,340\nMay 50,609,919 48,655,771\nJune 51,279,267 50,372,105\nJuly 56,836,381 52,431,690\nAugust 59,129,528 53,718,863\nInsured Mortgages Reported.\nHome mortgages accepted for in\nsurance by the Federal Housing Ad\nministration during July numbered\n9.159 and totaled $37,485,500 in\namount. For the first seven months\nof 1937 accepted mortgages numbered\n68,465 and totaled $281,216,816 in\namount, as compared with 56,051\nmortgages for $223,642,180 for the\nsame period of 1936, a gain of 22.1\nper cent in number and 25.7 per cent\nIn amount.\nThe National Housing Administra\ntion reports that mortgages accepted\nfor insurance in the District of Co\nlumbia in the first seven months of\nthis year numbered 726 and in amount\ntotaled $5,270,840.\nInsured mortgages in Maryland\nnumbered 3,622 and amounted to\n*15,499,985, in Virginia numbered\n8,743 and amounted to $17,719,544, and\nin West Virginia totaled 1,246 and\n$13,332,154 in amount.\nThe cumulative gro. i total of home\nmortgages for the whole country ac\ncepted for Insurance through July 31\nnumbered 220,223 and amounted to\n$890,260,833, the report states.\nTwenty-four per cent of the pay\nments due Washington department\nstores at the beginning of August were\npaid during the month, the Federal\nReserve Bank of Richmond reported\ntoday. This was a fair percentage,\nalthough receivables collected in the\nwhole fifth district reached 25.8 per\ncent. Baltimore payments were also\n\u2022head of the record here.\nStore stocks were 10 per cent higher\nin August this year than at the end\nof August, 1936. and ended the month\n4.5 per cent higher than at the end\nof July this year, the report added.\nIn the first eight months of 1937\n\u2022tore stocks in Washington were\nturned 2.566 times, against the lower\nfigure of 2.459 times tor the whole\nfifth district.\nGood Fall Earnings Forecast.\nAlthough financial sentiment is at a\nlow ebb, there are no present evidences\nthat the Fall business outlook has\ntaken on as dark a hue as recent\nstock market action would seem to\nIndicate. Business is still good, and\nsigns continue to point to an increas\ning tempo in the months ahead. While\nlabor costs are higher, it appears now\nthat earnings and dividends in most\nlines will continue to be substantial\nduring the remainder of 1937, United\nBusiness Sendee, Boston, says today.\nThe Washington office of the Rail\nway Express Co. announced today that\nJuly express traffic was 5.26 per cent\nahead of last year. With the business\nmoved by the express agency in July\nestimated at 9,757,901 shipments, the\nincrease recorded totals not far from\nhalf a million more than last year.\nThis is the thirty-third consecutive\nmonth that these monthly increases\nhave been reported.\nArundel Corp. of Baltimore, en\ngaged in the sand, gravel and con\ntracting business, reports for eight\nmonths ended August 31, 1937, profit\nof $850,336 after depreciation, etc.,\nbut before Federal income taxes, com\nparing with profit of $470,859 in first\neight months of 1936. Joseph B.\nHogan, president, stated that new\nrontracts received since June 30, 1937,\ntotaled $425,100, and contract work on\nha-.d is approximately $8,500,000.\noecuun mens.\nThe Safe Deposit Section of the Dis\ntrict Bankers\u2019 Association will hold its\nfirst meeting of the season Thursday\nevening at 8 o'clock in the board room\nof the American Security Trust Co.\nMrs. Helen R. Sharpe, Bank of Com\nmerce Savings, is chairman of the\nsection this year, the first woman to\nhold this office. The latest problems\nfacing safe deposit operations in the\nbanks will be discussed.\nJoseph A. Broderick, member of the\nFederal Reserve Board, will address\nthe Savings Banks Association of New\nYork at the annual convention to be\nheld at White Sulphur Springs, W.\nVa., October 20-22. Other speakers\nwill include William R. White, super\nintendent of banking in New York\nState.\nChairman Leo T. Crowley of the\nFederal Deposit Insurance Corp. will\naddress the Kentucky Bankers' Asso\nciation next Thursday at Louisville\non Government Supervision of Banks\nand Banking.\u201d\nNoted in Financial District.\nThe death of A. C. Beane, founder\nof the brokerage firm of Fenner\nBeane, will mean no change in the\nfirm\u2019s operations or capital structure,\nIt was stated at the office here today.\nHis death, at only 49 years of age,\nWas a great shock to his associates.\nWashington brokers were puzzled\nover the weakness of the New York\nstock market at the opening today.\nThere were as many explanations as\nstocks selling off, many of which were\nonly guesses. Rarely have there been\nmore different factors bearings on the\nmarket than at present, brokers say\nBankers assert that the old order ha*\nchanged and insist that business is\ngoing to improve this Fall, regardless\nof the market and any action it maj\ntake.\nBanks here have been noticed b>\nthe Chicago Federal Reserve Bank\nthat on September 26 Chicago will b\u00ab\non Central standard time instead ol\nCentral daylight time.\nGas Stock Leads Market\nThe new Washington Gas Light\npreferred stock led trading on the\nWashington Stock Exchange today\nopening at 99. The next transaction!\nincluded a 50-share block at 98%\nthe market closing at 98\nTwo bank stocks appeared on th<\nboard, Riggs National common record\ning a 5-share sale at 310 and Ameri\ncan Security Trust figuring in i\n10-share sale at 280.\nPotomac Electric Power 5'2 pe\noent preferred was strong, 21 and 2',\nshare sales taking place at 112.\n\n_ I I I i __ I I I ,1, f _ f\nTRANSACTIONS ON THE NEW YORK STOCK EXCHANGE\nB\u00bb Private Wire Direct to The Star.\nPrev 1937 Stock end Bales\u2014 Net\nHigh. Low. Dividend Rate. Add 00. High. Low. Close, chge\n85 63% Acme Steel (4)_ 3 68 66 66 -4\n22% 14% Adams Exp (.30g)_. 18 14% 14% 14%\n36 26% Addressog 1.40)_ 1 27 27 27 \u20141\n80% 61% Air Reduction (la). 26 65% 63 65%\n5% 1% Air-Way El Ap__ 6 1% 1% 1%\n15% 9% Alaska Jun (.60a)_ 20 10% 10 10%\n5% 1% Alleghany_ 104 2 1% 2\n69% 19 Alles pf *30 ww_ 6 19% 18 18 -2%\n52% 20% Alleg pr pf_ 10 19% 19 19 \u20141%\n45% 25 Alleg Steel (1.20g)_ 14 26% 25% 25% -1%\n27% 13 Allen Indus (1)__ 2 14 14 14\n258% 192 Allied Chem (6)_ 19 191 183 186 -6\n31% 18% Allied Mills (2g).__ 6 18% 17% 18\n21% 13% Allied Stores (.20a). 49 13% 13% 13%\n83% 63% Allis Chaim (2g)_ 35 55 63% 54% 1\niN tk Allis-Ch rts Sep 22.. 992 A b\n39*4 17% Alpha Portland (1). 4 17% 17% 17%\n8% 3% Amal Leath _ 4 4 3% 3%\n62% 34% Amal Leath pf (3)1 36 36 36 +1\n114% 71% Amerada (2)_ 8 74 72 73 \u20142\n101% 78 AmAgC(Del)6>4*. 4 77% 76 76 -4\n41% 20 Am Bank Note %g. 3 20% 20% 20%\n75% 59 Am Bank N pf (3).. 60s 60 60 60\n80% 45 Am Brake Sh (2g)__ .6 49 47 49 -2\n160 125 Am Brake S pf 6%~ 20b 128 128 128 +1\n121 90% Am Can (4a) _ 21 95% 94% 95% -2%\n174 152% Am Can pf (7)_ 1 156% 156% 166%\n71 30 Am Car Fy (%g)_ 9 31% 29 31% +1%\n33% 24% Am Ch&Cable lg__ 18 26 24 26\n112 98 Am Chicle (4a)_ 3 100 100 100\n23% 10 Am Colortype_ 2 11% 11% U%\u2014\n30% 17% Am Cornel Alco_ 6 19 19 19\n33% 20% Am Crys Sug 3.25g_ x 8 21 20% 21\n13% 5% Am Encaustic Til_ 11 6% 6% 6%\n17 9% Am European Sec._ 1 9% 9% 9%\n13%