.\nAssociated Press Financial Wrttar.\nNEW YORK, September 20\nPrices of leading stocks plunged Into\nnew low territory for the past 18\nmonths or longer in today's market.\nLosses of 1 to 9 points at the\nworst, however, were substantially re\nduced or canceled in many Instances\nin the final hour as some \"bargain\nhunting\" buying and short covering\nmade its appearance.\nBrokers could point to no outstand\ning news development as responsible\nfor resumption of the slide. Among\nfactors that might have caused heavy\ni selling at the start of the session, it\nj was said, were weakness of foreign\nsecurities markets and sizable aet\nj backs in several commodities,\nj Steels met a little support at tha\ntag-end of the day, notwithstanding\na downturn of more than 4 points in\nthis week's mill operations. Coppers,\nunder pressure throughout, failed to\nrevive to any great extent. Carriers\nand utilities were resistant.\nMotors stiffened, after a morning\nrelapse, on forecasts from automotive\ncenters that sales and production in\n1938 will equal if not exceed those of\nthe present year.\nTransfers were around 1,950,000\nshares.\nProminent on the off side the greater\npart of the time were shares of United\nStates Steel. Republic, Youngstown\nSheet ft Tube, National Steel, Wheel\ning Steel, Deere, Anaconda, Kenne\ncott, American Smelting, St. Joseph\nLead, Phelps Dodge, Howe Sound,\nCerro de Pasco, Caterpillar Tractor,\nMontgomery Ward, Sears Roebuck,\nMacy, Goodyear, Allied Chemical,\nPeoples Gas, Standard Oil of New\nJersey, Seaboard Oil, Texas Corp.,\nSkelly Oil, Johns-Manville. J. C. Pen\nney, Borg Warner, Crown Cork, Mon\nsanto Chemical. Coca-Cola, Hercules\nPower, Air Reduction, Owens-Illinois\nand Loew's.\nGeneral Motors and Chrysler man\naged to tack on modest plus signs near\nthe finish, but had difficulty in hold\ning them. Contesting the trend wer\u00ab\nSanta Pe, Pennsylvania, Southern\nRailway. Great Northern, American\nTelephone. Western Union, Electric\nPower St Light, Consolidated Edison,\nRadio Corp., Zenith Radio, Lima Loco\nmotive and Paramount.\nCHICAGO GRAIN\nST the Associated Preaa.\nCHICAGO, September 20\u2014Wildly\nIrregular fluctuations in September\ncom prices today carried the market\nover a range of more than B'/i cent*\nThe day's outcome was 2% cents\na bushel net loss in September corn.\nTransient rallies which hoisted Sep\ntember com at one time to more than\na cent above Saturday's finish were\nassociated with the circumstance that\nonly 126,000 bushels reduction of the\namount of uncompleted September\ncontracts was officially shown today to\nhave been effected Saturday.\nAt the close, corn futures varied from\n2% cents lower to 1% higher, com\npared with Saturday's finish. Septem\nber, 1.02'4; December, 63s*wheat,\n1 cent to 2\u20198 up; September, 1.04!\u00bb;\nDecember, 1.05-1.051*. and oats un\nchanged to advanced.\nWHEAT\u2014 Open. High. Low. CIOs*.\nSep. _ lop, 104% 1.01% 1.04%\nDec. ___. .1.03 1.05% 1.02% 1.05-06%\nMay 1.05% 1.07 1.04% 1.06%-07\nCORN\u2014\nSep. --.00% 1.05% .00% 1.02%\nOct. -.70% .70% .89% .70%\nDec. -.82% .84% .821, .83%-%\nj M*(ljAT8_- \u2022fin -61% 63 .64%\nSep. _ .31% .32 .31% .32\n1 Dec. .30% .30% .30% .30%-%\nI May -5l% -31'\u00bb .31%-%\nSOY BEANS\u2014\nOct. .98% .98% .98% .96%\nDec. .95% .95% .94% .95\nM*rye\u2014 37 37 '95^ 98\nSep. _.80 .81 .80 81%\nDec. -.78% .79% .78 .79%-%\nMay \u2022T8'4 -79% \u202277\u2019\u00bb .79%\nLARD\u2014\nSep. -11.20 11.32 11.12 11 32\nOct. 11.30 11.35 10.87 11 12\nDec. 10.87 10.87 10.45 10 72\nJan. 10 87 10.87 10.40 10.70\nBELLIES\u2014\nSfP- 16.37\nOct. 15.82 15.85 15.62 15.63\nChicago Cash Market.\nCash wheat, No. 3 hard, 1.0614-0714;\nNo. 3 Northern Spring, 1.0614; No. 3\nmixed, 1.04\u2018/i; com, No. 1 yellow. 1.03;\nNo. 2 yellow, 1.03-0512; oats. No. 1\nmixed, 33\u20194-341^; No. 2 mixed. 34'2;\nNo. 1 white, 34%-35; Rye, No. 2.\n82%-8514; No. 3, 82; barley, feed,\n48-57 nominal; malting, 64-92 nom\ninal; Timothy seed, 2.25-75 per cwt.\nBALTIMORE. September 20 <JPt.\u2014Wheat.\nNo. 2 red Winter, sarlicky, spot, domestic.\n1.06; September. 1.06.\nURUGUAYAN CONVERSION\nOFFER IS RECOMMENDED\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, September 30.\u2014The\nForeign Bondholders\u2019 Protective Coun\ncil, Inc., in a letter to holders of\nnearly $53,000,000 of defaulted dollar\nbonds of the Uruguayan government,\nhas recommended to their \"favor\nable consideration\u2019\u2019 a conversion of\nfer, terms of which were made pub\nlic by the Uruguayan ministry 4n\nWashington.\nThe plan contemplate* exchange of\nnew readjustment bonds, carrying\ngenerally higher rates of Interest than\nthe 3'2 per cent now being paid, and\nprovides for substantial sinking funds\nto retire the new issues, the announce\nment said.\nThe readjustment affects the ex\nternal debt 5 per cent gold bonds of\n1915, the 8 per cent external sinking\nfund gold bonds due August 1, 1946,\nthe 6 per cent external sinking fund\ngold bonds due May 1. 1960, and the\nS per cent external sinking fund gold\nbonds, public works loan, due May\n1, 1964.\n\nUTILITY HEAD PROMOTED.\nNEW YORK, September 30 OP).\u2014\nEdward F. Barrett, vice president and\niirector of Long Island Lighting Co.,\nm October 1 will become president of\nhe company, succeeding Ellis L. Phil\nips, who will become chairman of the\njoard.","height":"33520","width":"23864"}}
